STEP 5 — Enable Auto Public IP
Why?

Public EC2 needs:

automatic public IP
Enable

Go:

Subnets

Select:

Public-Subnet

Click:

Edit subnet settings

Enable:

Auto-assign public IPv4

Save.

STEP 6 — Create Security Groups
What is Security Group?

Acts like:

firewall for EC2

Controls:

inbound traffic
outbound traffic
Create Security Group

Go:

Security Groups

Click:

Create security group

Fill:

Field	Value
Name	Web-SG
VPC	Custom-VPC
Add Inbound Rules
Type	Port	Source
SSH	22	Your IP
HTTP	80	Anywhere
HTTPS	443	Anywhere
Why Restrict SSH?

Safer than:

0.0.0.0/0
STEP 7 — Launch EC2 Instances

Go:

Amazon EC2
Launch Public EC2

Click:

Launch Instance

Fill:

Field	Value
Name	Public-EC2
AMI	Amazon Linux
Type	t2.micro
Subnet	Public-Subnet
Auto Public IP	Enabled
Security Group	Web-SG

Launch.

Launch Private EC2

Again:

Launch Instance

Fill:

Field	Value
Name	Private-EC2
Subnet	Private-Subnet
Auto Public IP	Disabled

Launch.

STEP 8 — Connect to Public EC2
SSH Command

Example:

ssh -i "mykey.pem" ec2-user@PUBLIC-IP
Fix Permission Error (Windows)

Run:

icacls mykey.pem /inheritance:r
icacls mykey.pem /grant:r "%username%:R"
STEP 9 — Test Internet Access

Inside Public EC2:

Run:

ping google.com

Works because:

subnet connected to IGW

Correct Way To Access Private EC2

You must copy the key into public EC2 first.

🔹 Step 1 — From your local machine

Copy key to public EC2:

scp -i efs2.pem efs2.pem ec2-user@54.196.82.21:~
🔹 Step 2 — SSH into public EC2
ssh -i efs2.pem ec2-user@54.196.82.21
🔹 Step 3 — Set permissions

Inside public EC2:

chmod 400 efs2.pem
🔹 Step 4 — SSH into private EC2
ssh -i efs2.pem ec2-user@10.0.2.208

This should now work.

⚠️ Also Check Security Group

Your Private EC2 security group must allow:

Type	Port	Source
SSH	22	Web-SG

NOT 0.0.0.0/0.
